Description.LocalizedString: He tried to remember what happened before everything went black. He thought he could feel the caress of claws.
She blinked back her tears. When the world came back into focus, everything had changed.
The fog was especially cold, and a chill crossed her heart, even when the fog dissipated.
As the fog cleared, he realized he was laying on the cool ground, looking up at a dark sky.
She was prepared to run at the sound of menacing laughter, but the fog caught her first.
Even at her lowest point, she never felt as disoriented as she did when the fog cleared.
She let out a pained scream, cut short as she felt something pull her away.
He awoke with a start, his arms swinging at an enemy that wasn't there.
As he set down a trap, something told him this time would be different.
His heart swelled with joy. Something inside told him he would have a friend at last.
The sharp fingers released him at last, and he realized he was somewhere new.
Her rage subsided as she was freed from the fog and released into a new realm.
She looked up at the tempestuous skies just as a cold grip overtook her.
Every dream was the same. Her father, thirsty for blood. And a snake that saves her at the last moment.
The nightmares were relentless. Death lit up her father's eyes, and only the snake could save her.
It sat in the middle of the road, awaiting her arrival. It was always there for those in need of guidance.
It sat in the middle of the road, waiting for a lost soul to cross its path.
She woke up in a nondescript hotel room to find her latest artifact had been stolen.
His grandmother once told him the story of the trickster lizard, who taught the people to bury their dead.
After a tough practice, the coach told him to be a lion, and treat the ball like his prey.
She spent nights under the full moon in Greenville Cemetery, looking for material for her show.
She spent nights walking among the tombstones in Greenville Cemetery, hoping for a sign of the supernatural.
He didn't like the look of that orangutan from the moment it joined the circus, and he resolved to make its life miserable.
The rooster emerged from the flames, its beautiful cry harmonizing with the victim screaming on the pyre.
The rooster emerged from the flames, crowing as the victim died screaming.
The duelists met in the forest that night, but Vittorio refused to fight his challenger.
She stared at the ceiling of the hotel room, listening to her brother as he slept on the nearby couch, his snores rattling the windows.
He knew he had to get back at Thalita after she threw water on him while he slept. Only the best prank would do.
He swore under his breath when he realized his wallet was gone, thinking back to the strange woman who bumped into him that morning.
Kate was playing music in the park when a shy little girl tapped her shoulder. The child pointed to the guitar, then to her hearing aid.
Caleb took the blows and hit the ground. The men circled him, telling him they didn't want prisoners in their town.
He considered sharp, serrated blades as a possible improvement on his damaged form.
Kazan was sitting under the shadow of a tree. Flies flew around him, attracted by sweat and blood.
